Note:
Comprehensive Test Suite for Live Hot-Swapping Module

Tests all functionality of the live memory allocator and GC hot-swapping system including:
- Live switching of allocators and GC algorithms with zero downtime
- State transfer and migration between memory management components
- Safety checks and rollback mechanisms for failed swaps
- Production-ready hot-swapping with validation and error handling
- AI/agent-friendly hot-swapping APIs and integration
- Performance benchmarks for swap operations and overhead analysis
- Error handling and edge cases for hot-swapping scenarios
- Enterprise-grade reliability and robustness testing
:End Note

Import "../../../../../../src/stdlib/advanced/memory/live_hot_swapping" as HotSwapping
Import "../../../../../../src/stdlib/advanced/memory/custom_allocators" as Allocators
Import "../../../../../../src/stdlib/advanced/memory/gc_algorithms" as GCAlgorithms
Import "../../../../../../src/stdlib/advanced/utilities/common" as Common

Note: Test Configuration Constants
Let TEST_HEAP_SIZE be 16777216
Let TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE be 1024
Let TEST_SWAP_TIMEOUT be 5000
Let TEST_MAX_MEMORY_PRESSURE be 0.8
Let TEST_MAX_CPU_LOAD be 0.9

Note: Test Result Tracking
Let test_results be Dictionary[String, Boolean] containing
Let test_count be 0
Let passed_count be 0
Let failed_count be 0

Note: Helper Functions for Testing

Process called "run_test" that takes test_name as String and test_function as Function returns Boolean:
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    
    Try:
        Display message "Running test: " plus test_name
        Let result be test_function()
        
        If result:
            Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
            Set test_results[test_name] to true
            Display message "  ✓ PASS: " plus test_name
        Otherwise:
            Set failed_count to failed_count plus 1
            Set test_results[test_name] to false
            Display message "  ✗ FAIL: " plus test_name
            
        Return result
        
    Catch error:
        Set failed_count to failed_count plus 1
        Set test_results[test_name] to false
        Display message "  ✗ ERROR: " plus test_name plus " - " plus convert_to_string with value as error
        Return false

Process called "assert_equals" that takes actual as Any and expected as Any and message as String returns Boolean:
    If actual is equal to expected:
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Display message "  Assertion failed: " plus message
        Display message "    Expected: " plus convert_to_string with value as expected
        Display message "    Actual: " plus convert_to_string with value as actual
        Return false

Process called "assert_not_none" that takes value as Any and message as String returns Boolean:
    If value is not None:
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Display message "  Assertion failed: " plus message plus " - value is None"
        Return false

Process called "assert_true" that takes value as Boolean and message as String returns Boolean:
    If value is true:
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Display message "  Assertion failed: " plus message plus " - expected true, got false"
        Return false

Process called "assert_false" that takes value as Boolean and message as String returns Boolean:
    If value is false:
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Display message "  Assertion failed: " plus message plus " - expected false, got true"
        Return false

Process called "assert_greater_than" that takes actual as Number and expected as Number and message as String returns Boolean:
    If actual is greater than expected:
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Display message "  Assertion failed: " plus message
        Display message "    Expected > " plus convert_to_string with value as expected
        Display message "    Actual: " plus convert_to_string with value as actual
        Return false

Process called "assert_less_than" that takes actual as Number and expected as Number and message as String returns Boolean:
    If actual is less than expected:
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Display message "  Assertion failed: " plus message
        Display message "    Expected < " plus convert_to_string with value as expected
        Display message "    Actual: " plus convert_to_string with value as actual
        Return false

Process called "create_test_allocator" that takes allocator_type as String returns Allocators.Allocator:
    Note: Creates a test allocator for hot-swapping tests
    If allocator_type is equal to "pool":
        Return Allocators.create_pool_allocator with config as Allocators.PoolAllocatorConfig with:
            pool_size as TEST_HEAP_SIZE
            block_size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE
            alignment as 8
            thread_local as false
            metadata as dictionary containing
                "test_allocator" as true
                "type" as "pool"
    
    If allocator_type is equal to "stack":
        Return Allocators.create_stack_allocator with config as Allocators.StackAllocatorConfig with:
            stack_size as TEST_HEAP_SIZE
            alignment as 8
            thread_local as false
            metadata as dictionary containing
                "test_allocator" as true
                "type" as "stack"
    
    If allocator_type is equal to "buddy":
        Return Allocators.create_buddy_allocator with config as Allocators.BuddyAllocatorConfig with:
            heap_size as TEST_HEAP_SIZE
            min_block_size as 64
            max_block_size as 4096
            alignment as 8
            metadata as dictionary containing
                "test_allocator" as true
                "type" as "buddy"
    
    Otherwise:
        Return Allocators.create_linear_allocator with config as Allocators.LinearAllocatorConfig with:
            buffer_size as TEST_HEAP_SIZE
            alignment as 8
            allow_reallocation as true
            metadata as dictionary containing
                "test_allocator" as true
                "type" as "linear"

Process called "create_test_gc_algorithm" that takes gc_type as String returns GCAlgorithms.GCAlgorithm:
    Note: Creates a test GC algorithm for hot-swapping tests
    If gc_type is equal to "generational":
        Return GCAlgorithms.create_generational_gc with config as GCAlgorithms.GenerationalGCConfig with:
            heap_size as TEST_HEAP_SIZE
            young_generation_size as 4194304
            old_generation_size as 12582912
            collection_threshold as 0.8
            promotion_threshold as 5
            concurrent_enabled as true
            metadata as dictionary containing
                "test_gc" as true
                "type" as "generational"
    
    If gc_type is equal to "mark_sweep":
        Return GCAlgorithms.create_mark_sweep_gc with config as GCAlgorithms.MarkSweepGCConfig with:
            heap_size as TEST_HEAP_SIZE
            collection_threshold as 0.85
            concurrent_enabled as false
            compaction_enabled as true
            metadata as dictionary containing
                "test_gc" as true
                "type" as "mark_sweep"
    
    If gc_type is equal to "copying":
        Return GCAlgorithms.create_copying_gc with config as GCAlgorithms.CopyingGCConfig with:
            heap_size as TEST_HEAP_SIZE
            from_space_size as 8388608
            to_space_size as 8388608
            collection_threshold as 0.9
            metadata as dictionary containing
                "test_gc" as true
                "type" as "copying"
    
    Otherwise:
        Return GCAlgorithms.create_reference_counting_gc with config as GCAlgorithms.RefCountGCConfig with:
            heap_size as TEST_HEAP_SIZE
            cycle_detection_enabled as true
            deferred_deletion as true
            metadata as dictionary containing
                "test_gc" as true
                "type" as "reference_counting"

Process called "create_test_hot_swapper" returns HotSwapping.HotSwapper:
    Note: Creates a test hot swapper with default configuration
    Return HotSwapping.HotSwapper with:
        swap_allocator as HotSwapping.swap_allocator
        swap_gc as HotSwapping.swap_gc
        validate_swap as HotSwapping.validate_swap
        rollback_swap as HotSwapping.rollback_swap
        metadata as dictionary containing
            "test_swapper" as true
            "created_at" as Common.get_current_timestamp

Note: Core Hot-Swapping Tests

Process called "test_create_hot_swapper":
    Note: Tests creation of hot swapper with proper configuration
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    
    Let result1 be assert_not_none with value as hot_swapper and message as "Hot swapper should be created"
    Let result2 be assert_not_none with value as hot_swapper.swap_allocator and message as "Allocator swap function should be available"
    Let result3 be assert_not_none with value as hot_swapper.swap_gc and message as "GC swap function should be available"
    Let result4 be assert_not_none with value as hot_swapper.validate_swap and message as "Validation function should be available"
    Let result5 be assert_not_none with value as hot_swapper.rollback_swap and message as "Rollback function should be available"
    Let result6 be assert_not_none with value as hot_swapper.metadata and message as "Metadata should be initialized"
    
    Return result1 and result2 and result3 and result4 and result5 and result6

Process called "test_allocator_hot_swap_basic":
    Note: Tests basic allocator hot-swapping functionality
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let old_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
    Let new_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "stack"
    
    Note: Perform some allocations with old allocator to establish state
    Let allocation1 be old_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE
    Let allocation2 be old_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE multiplied by 2
    
    Let result1 be assert_not_none with value as allocation1 and message as "Old allocator should work before swap"
    Let result2 be assert_not_none with value as allocation2 and message as "Old allocator should handle multiple allocations"
    
    Note: Perform hot swap
    Let swap_start be Common.get_current_timestamp
    Let swap_success be hot_swapper.swap_allocator with old_allocator as old_allocator and new_allocator as new_allocator
    Let swap_end be Common.get_current_timestamp
    Let swap_duration be swap_end minus swap_start
    
    Let result3 be assert_true with value as swap_success and message as "Allocator hot swap should succeed"
    Let result4 be assert_less_than with actual as swap_duration and expected as TEST_SWAP_TIMEOUT and message as "Swap should complete within timeout"
    
    Note: Test new allocator functionality after swap
    Let new_allocation be new_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE
    Let result5 be assert_not_none with value as new_allocation and message as "New allocator should work after swap"
    
    Return result1 and result2 and result3 and result4 and result5

Process called "test_allocator_compatibility_validation":
    Note: Tests allocator compatibility validation before hot swap
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let compatible_old be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
    Let compatible_new be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "stack"
    
    Note: Test compatible allocators
    Let compatible_result be HotSwapping.validate_allocator_compatibility with old as compatible_old and new as compatible_new
    Let result1 be assert_true with value as compatible_result and message as "Compatible allocators should pass validation"
    
    Note: Create incompatible allocator (different alignment)
    Let incompatible_new be Allocators.create_pool_allocator with config as Allocators.PoolAllocatorConfig with:
        pool_size as TEST_HEAP_SIZE
        block_size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE
        alignment as 16
        thread_local as false
        metadata as dictionary containing
    
    Note: Test incompatible allocators
    Let incompatible_result be HotSwapping.validate_allocator_compatibility with old as compatible_old and new as incompatible_new
    Let result2 be assert_false with value as incompatible_result and message as "Incompatible allocators should fail validation"
    
    Return result1 and result2

Process called "test_gc_hot_swap_basic":
    Note: Tests basic GC algorithm hot-swapping functionality
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let old_gc be create_test_gc_algorithm with gc_type as "generational"
    Let new_gc be create_test_gc_algorithm with gc_type as "mark_sweep"
    
    Note: Simulate some GC activity with old algorithm
    old_gc.force_collection
    Let old_collections be old_gc.stats.collections
    
    Let result1 be assert_greater_than with actual as old_collections and expected as 0 and message as "Old GC should have collection history"
    
    Note: Perform hot swap
    Let swap_start be Common.get_current_timestamp
    Let swap_success be hot_swapper.swap_gc with old_gc as old_gc and new_gc as new_gc
    Let swap_end be Common.get_current_timestamp
    Let swap_duration be swap_end minus swap_start
    
    Let result2 be assert_true with value as swap_success and message as "GC hot swap should succeed"
    Let result3 be assert_less_than with actual as swap_duration and expected as TEST_SWAP_TIMEOUT and message as "GC swap should complete within timeout"
    
    Note: Test new GC functionality after swap
    new_gc.force_collection
    Let new_collections be new_gc.stats.collections
    
    Let result4 be assert_greater_than with actual as new_collections and expected as 0 and message as "New GC should work after swap"
    
    Return result1 and result2 and result3 and result4

Process called "test_gc_compatibility_validation":
    Note: Tests GC algorithm compatibility validation before hot swap
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let compatible_old be create_test_gc_algorithm with gc_type as "generational"
    Let compatible_new be create_test_gc_algorithm with gc_type as "mark_sweep"
    
    Note: Test compatible GC algorithms
    Let compatible_result be HotSwapping.validate_gc_compatibility with old as compatible_old and new as compatible_new
    Let result1 be assert_true with value as compatible_result and message as "Compatible GC algorithms should pass validation"
    
    Note: Create incompatible GC (different heap size)
    Let incompatible_new be GCAlgorithms.create_copying_gc with config as GCAlgorithms.CopyingGCConfig with:
        heap_size as TEST_HEAP_SIZE multiplied by 2
        from_space_size as 16777216
        to_space_size as 16777216
        collection_threshold as 0.9
        metadata as dictionary containing
    
    Note: Test incompatible GC algorithms
    Let incompatible_result be HotSwapping.validate_gc_compatibility with old as compatible_old and new as incompatible_new
    Let result2 be assert_false with value as incompatible_result and message as "Incompatible GC algorithms should fail validation"
    
    Return result1 and result2

Process called "test_swap_validation_system_conditions":
    Note: Tests swap validation under various system conditions
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let old_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
    Let new_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "stack"
    
    Note: Test validation under normal conditions
    Let normal_validation be hot_swapper.validate_swap with old as old_allocator and new as new_allocator
    Let result1 be assert_true with value as normal_validation and message as "Validation should pass under normal conditions"
    
    Note: Simulate high memory pressure (this would normally be checked by system metrics)
    Let memory_pressure_validation be hot_swapper.validate_swap with old as old_allocator and new as new_allocator
    Note: In real implementation, this would check actual system metrics
    Let result2 be assert_not_none with value as memory_pressure_validation and message as "Validation should handle memory pressure checks"
    
    Note: Test validation with uninitialized component
    Let uninitialized_allocator be None
    Let uninitialized_validation be hot_swapper.validate_swap with old as old_allocator and new as uninitialized_allocator
    Let result3 be assert_false with value as uninitialized_validation and message as "Validation should fail with uninitialized component"
    
    Return result1 and result2 and result3

Process called "test_rollback_mechanism":
    Note: Tests rollback mechanism for failed swaps
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let old_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
    Let new_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "stack"
    
    Note: Perform initial allocations
    Let allocation1 be old_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE
    Let allocation2 be old_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE multiplied by 2
    
    Let result1 be assert_not_none with value as allocation1 and message as "Old allocator should work before rollback test"
    Let result2 be assert_not_none with value as allocation2 and message as "Old allocator should handle multiple allocations"
    
    Note: Test rollback functionality
    Let rollback_success be hot_swapper.rollback_swap with old as old_allocator and new as new_allocator
    Let result3 be assert_true with value as rollback_success and message as "Rollback should succeed"
    
    Note: Verify old allocator still works after rollback
    Let post_rollback_allocation be old_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE
    Let result4 be assert_not_none with value as post_rollback_allocation and message as "Old allocator should work after rollback"
    
    Return result1 and result2 and result3 and result4

Note: State Transfer and Migration Tests

Process called "test_allocator_state_transfer":
    Note: Tests state transfer during allocator hot swap
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let old_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
    Let new_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "buddy"
    
    Note: Create allocations to establish state
    Let allocations be list containing
    For i from 0 to 9:
        Let allocation be old_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE plus (i multiplied by 64)
        Add allocation to allocations
    
    Let result1 be assert_equals with actual as length of allocations and expected as 10 and message as "Should have 10 allocations"
    
    Note: Get state before swap
    Let old_usage be old_allocator.stats.current_usage
    Let old_allocation_count be old_allocator.stats.allocation_count
    
    Let result2 be assert_greater_than with actual as old_usage and expected as 0 and message as "Old allocator should have usage before swap"
    Let result3 be assert_greater_than with actual as old_allocation_count and expected as 0 and message as "Old allocator should have allocations"
    
    Note: Perform swap with state transfer
    Let transfer_result be HotSwapping.prepare_allocator_swap with old as old_allocator and new as new_allocator
    Let result4 be assert_true with value as transfer_result.success and message as "State transfer preparation should succeed"
    
    Note: Complete the swap
    Let swap_success be hot_swapper.swap_allocator with old_allocator as old_allocator and new_allocator as new_allocator
    Let result5 be assert_true with value as swap_success and message as "Allocator swap with state transfer should succeed"
    
    Return result1 and result2 and result3 and result4 and result5

Process called "test_gc_heap_metadata_transfer":
    Note: Tests heap metadata transfer during GC hot swap
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let old_gc be create_test_gc_algorithm with gc_type as "generational"
    Let new_gc be create_test_gc_algorithm with gc_type as "copying"
    
    Note: Simulate heap activity
    old_gc.force_collection
    old_gc.force_collection
    old_gc.force_collection
    
    Let old_collections be old_gc.stats.collections
    Let old_heap_size be old_gc.heap_size
    
    Let result1 be assert_greater_than with actual as old_collections and expected as 2 and message as "Old GC should have collection history"
    Let result2 be assert_equals with actual as old_heap_size and expected as TEST_HEAP_SIZE and message as "Old GC should have correct heap size"
    
    Note: Test heap metadata transfer
    Let transfer_result be HotSwapping.transfer_heap_metadata with old_gc as old_gc and new_gc as new_gc
    Let result3 be assert_true with value as transfer_result.success and message as "Heap metadata transfer should succeed"
    
    Note: Verify new GC has received metadata
    Let result4 be assert_equals with actual as new_gc.heap_size and expected as old_heap_size and message as "New GC should inherit heap size"
    
    Return result1 and result2 and result3 and result4

Process called "test_atomic_swap_operations":
    Note: Tests atomic nature of swap operations
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let old_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
    Let new_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "linear"
    
    Note: Test atomic allocator switch
    Let atomic_result be HotSwapping.atomic_switch_allocator with old_allocator as old_allocator and new_allocator as new_allocator
    Let result1 be assert_true with value as atomic_result.success and message as "Atomic allocator switch should succeed"
    
    Note: Test atomic GC switch
    Let old_gc be create_test_gc_algorithm with gc_type as "mark_sweep"
    Let new_gc be create_test_gc_algorithm with gc_type as "reference_counting"
    
    Let gc_atomic_result be HotSwapping.atomic_switch_gc with old_gc as old_gc and new_gc as new_gc
    Let result2 be assert_true with value as gc_atomic_result.success and message as "Atomic GC switch should succeed"
    
    Return result1 and result2

Note: Production Readiness Tests

Process called "test_zero_downtime_guarantee":
    Note: Tests zero-downtime guarantee during hot swaps
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let old_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
    Let new_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "stack"
    
    Note: Start continuous allocation activity
    Let allocation_successful be true
    Let total_allocations be 0
    Let failed_allocations be 0
    
    Note: Simulate concurrent allocation during swap
    Let swap_start be Common.get_current_timestamp
    
    Note: Perform hot swap
    Let swap_success be hot_swapper.swap_allocator with old_allocator as old_allocator and new_allocator as new_allocator
    
    Let swap_end be Common.get_current_timestamp
    Let swap_duration be swap_end minus swap_start
    
    Note: During a real zero-downtime swap, allocations should continue to work
    Note: This test verifies the swap completes successfully
    Let result1 be assert_true with value as swap_success and message as "Zero-downtime swap should succeed"
    Let result2 be assert_less_than with actual as swap_duration and expected as TEST_SWAP_TIMEOUT and message as "Swap should be fast for zero downtime"
    
    Note: Test that new allocator works immediately after swap
    Let immediate_allocation be new_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE
    Let result3 be assert_not_none with value as immediate_allocation and message as "New allocator should work immediately after swap"
    
    Return result1 and result2 and result3

Process called "test_safety_mechanisms":
    Note: Tests safety mechanisms and error handling
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let old_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
    
    Note: Test swap with null new allocator
    Let null_swap_result be hot_swapper.swap_allocator with old_allocator as old_allocator and new_allocator as None
    Let result1 be assert_false with value as null_swap_result and message as "Swap with null allocator should fail safely"
    
    Note: Verify old allocator still works after failed swap
    Let post_failure_allocation be old_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE
    Let result2 be assert_not_none with value as post_failure_allocation and message as "Old allocator should work after failed swap"
    
    Note: Test GC swap safety
    Let old_gc be create_test_gc_algorithm with gc_type as "generational"
    Let null_gc_swap_result be hot_swapper.swap_gc with old_gc as old_gc and new_gc as None
    Let result3 be assert_false with value as null_gc_swap_result and message as "GC swap with null should fail safely"
    
    Note: Verify old GC still works after failed swap
    old_gc.force_collection
    Let post_failure_collections be old_gc.stats.collections
    Let result4 be assert_greater_than with actual as post_failure_collections and expected as 0 and message as "Old GC should work after failed swap"
    
    Return result1 and result2 and result3 and result4

Process called "test_resource_cleanup":
    Note: Tests proper resource cleanup after swaps
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let old_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
    Let new_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "buddy"
    
    Note: Get initial resource usage
    Let initial_memory be get_system_memory_usage
    
    Note: Perform allocations
    Let allocations be list containing
    For i from 0 to 19:
        Let allocation be old_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE
        Add allocation to allocations
    
    Note: Perform hot swap
    Let swap_success be hot_swapper.swap_allocator with old_allocator as old_allocator and new_allocator as new_allocator
    Let result1 be assert_true with value as swap_success and message as "Swap should succeed for cleanup test"
    
    Note: Clean up old allocator
    HotSwapping.cleanup_old_allocator with allocator as old_allocator
    
    Note: Verify resources are properly cleaned up
    Let post_cleanup_memory be get_system_memory_usage
    Let result2 be assert_not_none with value as post_cleanup_memory and message as "Memory usage should be tracked after cleanup"
    
    Note: Verify new allocator works after cleanup
    Let post_cleanup_allocation be new_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE
    Let result3 be assert_not_none with value as post_cleanup_allocation and message as "New allocator should work after cleanup"
    
    Return result1 and result2 and result3

Note: Performance and Stress Tests

Process called "test_swap_performance_benchmarks":
    Note: Tests performance benchmarks for hot swap operations
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    
    Note: Benchmark allocator swap performance
    Let allocator_swap_times be list containing
    For i from 0 to 4:
        Let old_alloc be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
        Let new_alloc be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "stack"
        
        Let start_time be Common.get_current_timestamp
        Let swap_result be hot_swapper.swap_allocator with old_allocator as old_alloc and new_allocator as new_alloc
        Let end_time be Common.get_current_timestamp
        Let swap_time be end_time minus start_time
        
        Add swap_time to allocator_swap_times
    
    Let avg_allocator_swap_time be calculate_average with times as allocator_swap_times
    Let result1 be assert_less_than with actual as avg_allocator_swap_time and expected as 1000 and message as "Average allocator swap should be under 1 second"
    
    Note: Benchmark GC swap performance
    Let gc_swap_times be list containing
    For i from 0 to 4:
        Let old_gc be create_test_gc_algorithm with gc_type as "generational"
        Let new_gc be create_test_gc_algorithm with gc_type as "mark_sweep"
        
        Let start_time be Common.get_current_timestamp
        Let swap_result be hot_swapper.swap_gc with old_gc as old_gc and new_gc as new_gc
        Let end_time be Common.get_current_timestamp
        Let swap_time be end_time minus start_time
        
        Add swap_time to gc_swap_times
    
    Let avg_gc_swap_time be calculate_average with times as gc_swap_times
    Let result2 be assert_less_than with actual as avg_gc_swap_time and expected as 2000 and message as "Average GC swap should be under 2 seconds"
    
    Return result1 and result2

Process called "test_stress_testing":
    Note: Tests hot swapping under stress conditions
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let successful_swaps be 0
    Let failed_swaps be 0
    
    Note: Perform multiple rapid swaps
    For i from 0 to 9:
        Let old_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
        Let new_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "linear"
        
        Note: Simulate some load
        For j from 0 to 4:
            old_allocator.allocate with size as TEST_ALLOCATION_SIZE plus (j multiplied by 32)
        
        Let swap_result be hot_swapper.swap_allocator with old_allocator as old_allocator and new_allocator as new_allocator
        If swap_result:
            Set successful_swaps to successful_swaps plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Set failed_swaps to failed_swaps plus 1
    
    Let result1 be assert_greater_than with actual as successful_swaps and expected as 7 and message as "Most swaps should succeed under stress"
    Let result2 be assert_less_than with actual as failed_swaps and expected as 3 and message as "Few swaps should fail under normal stress"
    
    Return result1 and result2

Process called "test_concurrent_swap_safety":
    Note: Tests safety of concurrent swap operations
    Let hot_swapper be create_test_hot_swapper
    Let old_allocator be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "pool"
    Let new_allocator1 be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "stack"
    Let new_allocator2 be create_test_allocator with allocator_type as "buddy"
    
    Note: Attempt concurrent swaps (in real implementation, this would be properly synchronized)
    Let swap1_result be hot_swapper.swap_allocator with old_allocator as old_allocator and new_allocator as new_allocator1
    Let swap2_result be hot_swapper.swap_allocator with old_allocator as old_allocator and new_allocator as new_allocator2
    
    Note: Only one swap should succeed, or both should handle concurrency safely
    Let result1 be assert_not_none with value as swap1_result and message as "First swap should have a result"
    Let result2 be assert_not_none with value as swap2_result and message as "Second swap should have a result"
    
    Note: At least one operation should succeed or fail gracefully
    Let at_least_one_defined be (swap1_result is not None) or (swap2_result is not None)
    Let result3 be assert_true with value as at_least_one_defined and message as "At least one swap result should be defined"
    
    Return result1 and result2 and result3

